Case Study III

Emily Schmidt and Genta Mehmeti

2023-05-05

Working with Dirty Data I
Frederic Fuchsbau is a marketing manager of the well-known French retail company Galeries Lafayette. Due to declining sales the CMO has called for a project to better understand how customers view Galeries Lafayette and how these perceptions drive loyalty and commitment to Galeries Lafayette. Essentially the key goal of the project is to identify the key drivers of brand equity for Galeries Lafayette. Frederic Fuchsbau partnered with a research consultancy to get the necessary expertise on board and move the project forward. In an initial project step 20 depth interviews were conducted to get an understanding how its customers view Galeries Lafayette. What they like and what they dislike about Galeries Lafayette and how Galeries Lafayette could improve. Based on the insights generated a questionnaire was designed an mailed to 5000 customers of Galeries Lafayette with a stamped return envelope. About 600 customers returned a completed questionnaire. In a first step you should run a confirmatory factor analysis to determine the dimensions by which Galeries Lafayette is perceived by its customers.

Working with Dirty Data II
The data set with the results from the survey is available on Moodle under the name Case Study III_Structural Equation Modeling.csv. The data set contains a range of items measuring image perceptions, loyalty, commitment and more. In order to solve problem 1 please focus on the questions image1 to image22 in the data set. These are the 22 image statements that every respondent had to answer in the survey. The question addressed various topics, which had surfaced in the 20 depth interviews conducted prior to the survey. The question were answered with a Likert-scale anchored with 1 does not apply at all and 7 does apply completely. The image questions ranged from Large Range of Assortment to Intimate Atmosphere. Prior to conducting the confirmatory factor analyses run an exploratory factor analyses in R to get an initial idea by which dimensions customers perceive Galeries Lafayette. In the file all 22 image items are proposed to measure different constructs or perceptual dimensions. Then, based on these insights please apply the confirmatory factor analyses.
- Resource: Case Study III

There are 553 observations with 22 variables that relate to image statements that every respondent had to answer in the survey. Throughout the data frame above, there are values of 999 which represent missing values.

sum(lafayette_122 == 999) # 345 NA values which were originally "999" vales
## [1] 345
# Replace all 999 values with the mean of each column
lafayette_122 = data.frame(sapply(lafayette_122,function(x) ifelse((x == 999),NA,as.numeric(x))))

# Remove rows with missing data
lafayette_122 <- na.omit(lafayette_122) # 385 observations, 30% of data is missing

# Replace NA with column mean
for (i in 1:ncol(lafayette_122)) {
  col_mean <- median(lafayette_122[,i], na.rm = TRUE)
  lafayette_122[is.na(lafayette_122[,i]), i] <- col_mean
}

There are 345 999 values that need to be replaced. Therefore, we will remove each row with a missing value that was previously represented by 999. If this approach was not recommended from class, we would have justified either using the column mean or median depending on the distribution of the variables.

The histograms provide the reader a clear understanding about the distribution of the each survey question. There are several observations that help depict how customers responded:

  1. A majority of the questions have most responses between 4 to 6.

  2. Out of the 22 distributions, there are several that appear to be skewed. This will be further analyzed below.

Since there are assumptions of normality that need to be fulfilled, it is critical to understand the skewness and kurtosis of each column. To be normal, a data set needs to be symmetric and have a bell-shaped curve.

Skewness range: A negative skew means that the tail of the distribution is longer on the left side. Therefore, most of the data is concentrated on the right side of the histogram. The opposite can be said about positive skewness. For all 22 questions, they all appear to have a negative skew. The most prominent skewed distributed can be seen in \(Im14\) and \(Im8\). Based on prior class discussion though, the skewness is considered relatively small due to the context of the data.

Kurtosis range: The closer the value is to zero, the more flat the distribution relative to a normality. There are several questions where their values are within an absolute value of 1.6, which would insinuate that the distributions are more flat than other distributions and possibly non-normal. Since these values are around +/- 1.6 or above/below, we can conclude that they are not flat, but have a bell-shape. Anything above zero would have a leptokurtic distribution, peaked higher than the expected normal distribution. If the value is negative, it follows a platykurtic distribution, indicating that it is flatter. This can occur when the data is more spread out and has a lower concentration around the mean.

2 Part II - Exploratory Factor Analyses

2.1 Correlation Matrix

corr_lafayette_122 <- cor(lafayette_122)

corrplot(corr_lafayette_122, tl.col = "black", number.cex = 0.8, method = 'color', order = 'alphabet')

corrplot(corr_lafayette_122, tl.col = "black", number.cex = 0.8, order = "hclust", tl.cex = 0.5, addrect = 8, rect.col = 'blue')

# Resource [1]

corrplot(corr_lafayette_122, tl.col = "black", number.cex = 0.8, order = "hclust", tl.cex = 0.5, addrect = 9, rect.col = 'blue')

# Resource [1]

A primary goal in factor analysis is to ensure that the variables are suitable to obtain distinct dimensions in order to reduce the number of items to explain and interpret the results. The correlation matrix shows that some variables are highly correlated with one another while others have almost no relationship. Here are several examples:

  • \(Im3\) and \(Im4\) have the highest correlation at 91%, with \(Im2\) and \(Im1\) at 87%.

  • There are an additional five relationships that have a correlation between 73% and 85%, indicated by the larger and darker blue squares.

There are two other correlation matrices with blue boxes around the questions that need to be considered. These boxes indicate how many possible factors will be used. In the first one, a hypothetical 8-factor solution shows that there are eight groupings with at least two questions each. In the second correlation plot, 9-factors represented. Here, we see the box that previously had \(Im9\), \(Im6\), and \(Im7\), separate into two boxes. \(Im9\) is now a standalone question within its own factor, and this is possibly due to not having a high loading in any of the other factors. This could be problematic since that question has no relation with any other survey questions. \(Im9\) will be on the preliminary watch list.

Resource [1] https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/corrplot/vignettes/corrplot-intro.html\

2.2 Barletts Test of Sphericity

bart_spher(lafayette_122)
##  Bartlett's Test of Sphericity
## 
## Call: bart_spher(x = lafayette_122)
## 
##      X2 = 6451.238
##      df = 231
## p-value < 2.22e-16

The Bartlett-Test (test of sphericity) tests the hypothesis that the sample originates from a population, where are variables are uncorrelated. The main assumption is that the variables in a population are normally distributed. Bartlett-Test of Sphericity is highly significant. The p-value is very small,the \(H_0\) that all correlations between IVs are 0 can be rejected (\(H_0\): correlation matrix = identity matrix). Additional tests like the Kaiser-Meyer-Olkin (KMO) or Measure of Sampling Adequacy (MSA) can be utilized and may be more appropriate.

2.3 Kaiser-Meyer-Olkin Criterion

KMO_Test <- KMOS(lafayette_122)
KMO_Test
## 
## Kaiser-Meyer-Olkin Statistics
## 
## Call: KMOS(x = lafayette_122)
## 
## Measures of Sampling Adequacy (MSA):
##       Im1       Im2       Im3       Im4       Im5       Im6       Im7       Im8 
## 0.8244624 0.8224640 0.8640362 0.8542604 0.9546668 0.8224827 0.8448231 0.9300079 
##       Im9      Im10      Im11      Im12      Im13      Im14      Im15      Im16 
## 0.9380091 0.8285789 0.9113882 0.8789413 0.8722220 0.8267452 0.9647563 0.9092200 
##      Im17      Im18      Im19      Im20      Im21      Im22 
## 0.8644991 0.8550678 0.9400714 0.8266391 0.9149654 0.8793157 
## 
## KMO-Criterion: 0.8770975

The KMO test measures sampling adequacy (MSA) by taking the ratio of the sum of squared correlations to the sum of squared correlations plus the sum of squared partial correlations. If the value is greater than 0.6, the data can be reduced to less dimensions by meeting the required threshold. For this factor analysis, it surpasses that requirement at 0.88, which means that the data is a good fit for factor analysis since it has a value closer to 1.

# Compute the Kaiser-Meyer-Olkin (KMO) measure for a dataset with 133 variables
kmo_results <- KMO(lafayette_122)

# Create a data frame with the diagonal values and their indices
df <- data.frame(values = diag(kmo_results$ImCov), index = 1:length(diag(kmo_results$ImCov)))

# Plot the diagonal values using ggplot2
ggplot(df, aes(x = index, y = values)) +
  geom_point(size = 2, color = ifelse(df$values > 0.5, "blue", "black")) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 9,lwd = .05,color = "black") +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 11,lwd = .05,color = "black") +
  scale_x_continuous(name = "Variable Index") +
  scale_y_continuous(name = "KMO's Imcor") +
  ggtitle("Diagonal Elements of KMO's Matrix") +
  theme_minimal()

Lowest value in Anti-Image correlation is for \(Im2\) (Assortment Variety), but it will most likely not be on the watch list since it is not considered an outlier within these questions. This is due to the value falling in line with \(Im6\) and has a small gap to the second and third questions.

The Anti-Image Correlation measure the sampling adequacy for each individual variable. From using this type of matrix, items that do not correlate with any of the factors can be easily identified. If a value is below 0.5, the corresponding variable should be removed from the analysis. As seen above, all elements are above that threshold.

Additionally, it is interesting to look at the MSA diagonals because it relates to how well those factors/dimensions have been covered throughout the survey questions. Both \(Im9\) and \(Im11\) are a bit higher (above 0.5) compared to every other question according to the blue dots. Therefore, we add \(Im11\) to the watch list with \(Im9\).

  geom_abline(intercept = 1, slope = 0, color = "#D2B48C") + 
  theme_minimal()

The graph above shows a screeplot, which is a graphical representation of eigenvalues by ordering them according to their size. There are two ways to analyze this chart, by the numerical representation of the eigenvlaue or subjectively. The analyst shoul retain the eigenvalues above the break at 1 or elbow of the curve. To use the subjective rule, visualizing the elbow can be difficult as multiple interpretations can occur. If we had to guess, it would most likely be 8-factors or 9-factors. Therefore, a more concrete approach is to look at the Kaiser criterion. The main rule to follow is that only eigenvalues greater than 1 should be extracted. If that eigenvalue is less than 1, this means that the factor contributes less than a single variable in explaining total variance. It is seen within the screeplot that there is an 6-factor solution by the points that are on or above the tan line indicating which eigenvalues are above that threshold.

The parallel plot review how many factors are estimated to be the best solution. The recommended number of factors is 7. If we strictly look at the eigenvalues though, there would be only two factors above 1.

To obtain the best model, we will test several scenarios with different factors to see which ones have the optimal metrics to choose how many factors should be used. Here is a quick summary of the six elements below:

  • The BIC statistic represents the Bayesian information criterion.
  • The crms statistic is a modified version of rms that accounts for degrees of freedom.
  • The factor models ability to reproduce the correlation matrix is assessed by the fit statistic.
  • The objective value is obtained by minimizing a function using maximum likelihood procedure.
  • The rms metric measures the sum of squared off-diagonal residuals divided by the degrees of freedom.
  • The TLI index calculates the Tucker Lewis Index of factoring reliability.

2.6 Principal Axis Factoring Possiblities

# we initiate and empty dataframe which will record our criteria values
fit_df <- matrix(nrow = 10, ncol = 6)
colnames(fit_df) <- c("fit", "objective", "rms", "crms", "TLI", "BIC")
fit_df <- as.data.frame(fit_df)

# we compute the factor analysis for nfactors between 1 and 13 and record criteria results in fit_df
for (i in 1:10) {
  FA <- fa(lafayette_122, nfactors = i, rotate = "varimax", fm = "pa")
  fit_df[i, 1] <- FA$fit
  fit_df[i, 2] <- FA$objective
  fit_df[i, 3] <- FA$rms
  fit_df[i, 4] <- FA$crms
  fit_df[i, 5] <- FA$TLI
  fit_df[i, 6] <- FA$BIC
}

rm(i, FA)
# Resource [2]
fit_df %>% gather() %>%

In factor analysis, it is important to understand the extent of each variable as it relates to the underlying constructs represented by the factors. When these unique values are high, it suggests that the variable may not be well equipped by the proposed factors. In the scenarios, \(Im9\) and \(Im11\) are higher than all the other questions. This means they are less relevant and should continue to be on the watch list.

We will run different combinations of factors against the watch list variables to analyze how the loadings compare to the relative factors. As a reminder, \(Im9\) is being removed alone in some of these models because of the correlation matrix results and the uniqueness of that variable compared to all others.

Principal Axis Factoring has been run on for the six models and we observe the loading matrix here as a correlation plot. The first model has 8-factors without question 9 since it had a high MSA diagonal and by its standalone nature when looking at the blue boxes within the first correlation matrix. Within all the factors, the loadings appear to be relatively high with only \(Im15\) possibly being loaded lower in multiple factors. Therefore, \(Im15\) will be added to the watch list. The second model looks at 8-factors without question 11 since the MSA diagonal was once again higher than all other questions and its lower communality. Now, it appears that \(Im9\) follows suit with \(Im15\) and is loaded in multiple factors. The third model with 8-factors but now excluding questions 9 and 11, which shows how \(Im15\) is still problematic. Out of the three 8-factor models, 8-factor without \(Im9\) has the lowest BIC, 8-factor without \(Im9\) an \(Im11\) has the lowest rms, and best fit and TLI.

Moving onto the 9-factor solutions, it is immediately clear 9-factor without images 9 and 11 are not loaded on anything. The 9-factor solution without \(Im11\) is more promising but \(Im9\) appears to be loaded low within multiple factors once again. The last model, 9-factor solution without \(Im9\), now \(Im11\) is loaded in PA4 and PA9 without any other questions in PA9. Out of the 9-factor solution, none of the BIC values are lower than an 8-factor model, but 9-factor w/o 9_11 has the best fit of all six models and lowest rms. For TLI, all the 9-factor solutions are slightly higher. To quickly check if a 9-factor solution is feasible, we look at the loadings.

The loadings are an important estimation when it comes to analyzing the correlation between each observed variable and the proposed factors. They can be thought of as weights. When the weight is higher, that indicates the question is associated with the factor. Ideally, the weights of 0.7 or above would be considered good loadings. Therefore, it is important to identify those that may not be as highly loaded as they could be problematic.

Between the first two models, 8-factors without \(Im9\) and 8-factors without \(Im11\) have the same cumulative variance at 77.1%, and \(Im15\) has the lowest loading. When \(Im9\) is excluded, in PA8, \(Im19\) has a lower loading of 0.546, \(Im11\) is with PA4 at a loading of 0.560, and \(Im8\) is basically split into two loadings. \(Im8\), \(Im11\), \(Im15\), and \(Im19\) should be on the watch list. In the second model, now \(Im9\) has the lowest loading, followed by \(Im15\), \(Im19\), and \(Im8\)s split has a smaller gap as they approach 50% more.

When eliminating both \(Im9\) and \(Im11\), the total variance increases to 78.7%. In addition, \(Im8\) slightly improves to show that but still has higher loadings in both that make it harder to determine where it would fit. \(Im15\) continues to be the lowest loading, while \(Im19\)s weight improves from the second model, but worsens from the first. We will look at the communalities of these three models to determine next steps.

2.8 EFA Final Factor Solution

fa(lafayette_122[, -c(8, 9, 11, 15)], nfactors = 8, rotate = "varimax", fm = "pa") |>  
  fa.diagram(sort = TRUE, errors = TRUE)

The factor diagram provides an overview of the solution by presenting eight factors and indicating how much each item correlates with them.
- Resources: https://nickmichalak.com/post/2019-02-14-using-principal-components-or-common-factor-analysis-in-social-psychology/using-principal-components-or-common-factor-analysis-in-social-psychology/ and https://rpubs.com/zoexoe/592607

The final solution is the model with 8-factors, without images 8, 9, 11, 15. Throughout this analysis, there were several reasons why those four questions would be removed. First, \(Im9\)s relationship to other images was relatively low. When looking at the correlation matrices, when the factor was changed from 8 to 9, we saw how \(Im9\) was separated to be a standalone variable within its own factor. Second, the MSA diagonals gave a clue that images 9 and 11 may not be fit for the final model since they were not covered well in the survey. Once we figured out that the model would either have 8 or 9 factors, we ran a uniqueness analysis that showed how \(Im9\) and \(Im11\) stood apart from all other questions in an 8-factor and 9-factor solution. After combinations of those models were completed, we immediately knew removing question 9 due to the cumulative variance increasing once it was excluded, and the fact that it had the lowest loading. After running more comparing the three 8-factor models with a combination of excluding \(Im8\), \(Im9\), \(Im11\), \(Im15\), and \(Im19\), it was clear that \(Im11\) also needed to be removed due to the continued low communality value.At the end, \(Im8\) was exclued because of its loading in two factors, and \(Im15\) was always had the lowest loading throughout all the matrices. Therefore, we ended up with a model that explains 80.0% cumulative variance. The eight factors can be described as:

Factor 1: Aesthetic
- \(Im4\): Creative Decoration of Sales Area
- \(Im3\): Artistic Decoration of Sales Area
- \(Im5\): Appealing Arrangement of Shop Windows

Factor 3: Retail_Environment
- \(Im20\): Relaxing Shopping
- \(Im22\): A Great Place to Stroll
- \(Im21\): Intimate Shop Atmosphere

Factor 4: High_end_Brands
- \(Im13\): Up to date Designer Brands
- \(Im12\): Luxury Brands

Factor 5: Assortment
- \(Im1\): Large Assortment
- \(Im2\): Assortment Variety

Factor 2: Gourmet
- \(Im10\): Gourmet Food
- \(Im14\): Gourmet Specialties

Factor 7: French
- \(Im7\): French Savoir-vivre
- \(Im6\): France

Factor 6: Fashionable
- \(Im17\): Are Trendy
- \(Im18\): Are Hip

Factor 8: Corporate_Image
- \(Im16\): Appearance Towards Customers
- \(Im19\): Professional Organization

Exploratory Factor Analysis (EFA) is utilized when it is not known how many factors there are between the questions and which factors are determined by which items. Confirmatory Factor Analysis (CFA) though uses a strong theory about the structure. Within the EFA, factors are assumed to be uncorrelated because we used varimax rotation. However, in CFA, they have the possibility of having a relationship. Therefore, we will compare these two methods by now running the CFA. Since the best model in EFA was a 8-factor solution without questions 8, 9 and 11 and 15, confirmatory analysis will run two models based off of this result. Recall that \(Im19\) remained on the watch list due to its relatively low loading and will be explored again.

3 Part III: Confirmatory Factor Analysis

# Replace missing values (999) with NA
lafayette[lafayette == 999] <- NA

3.1 CFA: 8-Factor without Im8, Im9, Im11, and Im15

# 8-factor model without Im8, Im9, Im11, and Im15
model1 <- "
Aesthetic =~ Im4 + Im3 + Im5
Retail_Environment =~ Im20 + Im22 + Im21
Assortment =~ Im1 + Im2 
French =~ Im7 + Im6 
Gourmet =~ Im10 + Im14 
High_end_Brands =~ Im13 + Im12
Fashionable =~ Im17 + Im18
Corporate_Image =~ Im16 + Im19
"

fit1 <- cfa(model1, data = lafayette, missing = "ML")
summary(fit1, fit.measures = TRUE, standardized = TRUE)

The first confirmatory is based on EFAs best model with 8-factors, without question 8, 9, 11, and 15. Even though we have concluded that the best model was with

Throughout the summary, there are several key elements to discuss:

  • Estimator: The maximum likelihood (ML) estimator was used to fit the model.

  • Optimization method: The nonlinear optimization method NLMINB was used to optimize the model parameters.

  • Model Test User Model: The user model was compared to a baseline model. The test statistic for the user model was 203.508, with 107 degrees of freedom and a p-value of 1.90. A low Chi-value (under consideration of degrees of freedom) indicates a good fit if it should be below 5. The test statistic for the baseline model was 7217.692, with 153 degrees of freedom and a p-value of 47.17. Therefore, it appears that the user model performed significantly better than the baseline model, as indicated by a lower test statistic.

  • Fit Indices: The Comparative Fit Index (CFI) is 0.986, meaning that the model would be accepted.

  • AIC and BIC: Both of these measure of model selection that help to compare different models and choose the best one for a given data set. Therefore, to make meaning out of AIC at 24633.709 and a BIC of 24987.568, we will compare this model to an additional two to determine the if the EFA model aligns with CFA.

  • Root mean square error of approximation (RMSEA): The RMSEA for the user model is 0.04, with a 90% confidence interval from 0.032 to 0.049. This interval does not include zero, and means that it is statistically significant. Ideally, the measure of discrepancy between the observed data and the model should have values closer to zero, indicating a better fit. A 4.0% RMSEA would be considered an acceptable fit.

The second confirmatory is based on the EFAs best model with the additional removal of \(Im19\). This question was the last one in the watch list, and wanted to ensure it was examined. There are several key elements to discuss:

  • Model Test User Model: The user model was compared to a baseline model. The test statistic for the user model was 189.024, with 92 degrees of freedom and a p-value of 2.05. The test statistic for the baseline model was 6782.213, with 136 degrees of freedom and a p-value of 49.87, Therefore, it appears that the user model performed significantly better than the baseline model, as indicated by a lower test statistic that is a good fit since it falls below 5. But, this p-value is higher than the first model.

  • Fit Indices: The Comparative Fit Index (CFI) is 0.985, which indicates a lower fit compared to the prior model. Overall though, this model would be accepted.

  • AIC and BIC: Both of these measure of model selection that help to compare different models and choose the best one for a given data set. The AIC is 23384.393 and has a BIC of 23720.991, which are smaller than the first model.

  • Root mean square error of approximation (RMSEA): The RMSEA for the user model is 0.044, with a 90% confidence interval from 0.035 to 0.057. This models RMSEA is bigger than the first model, but still falls into the category of being an acceptable fit.

3.3 CFA Final Factor Solution

Due to the lowest p-value and RMSEA combined, and highest CFI, the best CFA model seems to be the first model, 8-factors without questions 8, 9, 11, and 15. It was seen that BIC and AIC were better in the second model that also excluded \(Im19\), but that is not enough of a reason to change the model when the p-value and RMSE are lower. This means that the EFA and CFA models produce the same results.

3.6 Cronbachs Alpha

Cronbachs \(\alpha\) provides an overall assessment of a measures reliability for a set of survey items. If the \(\alpha\) is relatively high, this means that there is internal consistency between the questions. Unfortunately, this does not show any dimensionality and that is why the EDA was in part utilized above.

Note: Only the images were used for Cronbach \(\alpha\) to ensure that all questions had no missing values. Otherwise, most of the values would be below the threshold of 0.70.

# Create a data frame with two columns
my_table1 <- data.frame(
  Model = c("Aesthetic", "Retal_Envrnmnt", "Assortment", "Cultural_Refinement", "Gourmet", "High_end_Brands", "Fashionable", "Corporate_Imag"),
  Alpha = c(91.3, 88.6, 92.9, 88.2, 93.3, 85.9, 90.2, 80.6))

According to the lecture, we look at modification indices to help us to diagnose the problem. These indices measure how much chi-square is expected to decrease if this particular parameter is set free and the model is reestimated. Therefore, the modification index is approximately equal to the difference in chi-square between two models in which one parameter is fixed or constrained in one model and free in the other, all other parameters being estimated in both models. When there is a large modification index, it shows the parameter that improves the fit most when set free. In the 8-factor solution model, there appears to be no issues with large values of modification indices, which would mean that those values are highly correlated.

4 Question 1

What are the dimensions by which Galeries Lafayette is perceived? Please explain your findings and rational for your final result.

There were two factor analyses completed, exploratory and confirmatory. The EFA is a statistical technique that is used to minimize data to a smaller set of summary variables and to explore the underlying theoretical structure of the phenomena [3]. However, CFA is a multivariate statistical procedure that is utilized to test how well the measured variables represent the number of constructs [4]. The first step to analyzing the 22 image questions was to conduct an EFA. All of the details can be found under Part II as to how and why this specific model was chosen. The final model has 8-factors, and excluded questions 8, 9, 11, and 15 which were about Expertise in French Traditional Cuisine, French Fashion, High-quality Cosmetics, and Professional Selection of Brands. Therefore, the eight dimensions that were considered are the following:

  1. Aesthetic

  2. Retail_Environment

  3. Gourmet

  4. Assortment

  5. French

  6. High_end_Brands

  7. Fashionable

  8. Corporate_Image

In the next analysis under CFA, the results results in the same dimensions. For more details about this final model, please refer to Part III. The finalized factors are:

  1. Aesthetic

  2. Retail_Environment

  3. Gourmet

  4. Assortment

  5. French

  6. High_end_Brands

  7. Fashionable

  8. Corporate_Image

Overall, Galaries Lafayette should rely on the CFAs models eight dimensions above when trying to understand how customers view and perceive this business.

5 Part IV: Structural Equation Model (SEM)

The mediators are given as Customer Satisfaction (SAT1_4) and Affective Commitment (COM1_4). Since there are various columns for each, a CFA model was run to combine the variables into one mediator. In this step, we did the same thing for the outcomes, Repurchase Intention (C_REP1_4) and Cocreation Intention (C_CRI1_4). Furthermore, we will build our SEM model below to idenitfy indirect, direct and total effects.

5.1 Constructing SEM

# Define the measurement model for the 8 factors without q/ 8,9,11,15
Latent_Factors <- 
' # Latent Factors
Aesthetic =~ Im4 + Im3 + Im5
Retail_Environment =~ Im20 + Im22 + Im21
Assortment =~ Im1 + Im2
French =~ Im7 + Im6 
Gourmet =~ Im10 + Im14
High_end_Brands =~ Im13 + Im12
Fashionable =~ Im17 + Im18
Corporate_Image =~ Im16 + Im19

# Define the latent variables
# Latent Variables
COM1_4 =~ COM_A1 + COM_A2 + COM_A3 + COM_A4
SAT1_3 =~ SAT_1 + SAT_2 + SAT_3
C_REP1_4 =~ C_REP1 + C_REP2 + C_REP3
C_CR1_4 =~ C_CR1 + C_CR2 + C_CR3'

#Define structural model with the mediators and latent factors
Regression_Paths <- 
'#regression paths factors on SAT
SAT1_3 ~ a*Aesthetic + b*Retail_Environment + c*Assortment + d*French + e*Gourmet + f*High_end_Brands + g*Fashionable + h*Corporate_Image

#regression paths factor on COM
COM1_4 ~ i*Aesthetic + j*Retail_Environment + k*Assortment + l*French + m*Gourmet + n*High_end_Brands + o*Fashionable + p*Corporate_Image

# Define structural model with the mediators and outcomes
#direct effect of the mediatiors on REP
C_REP1_4 ~ q*SAT1_3 + s*COM1_4
#direct effect of the mediators on CRQ
C_CR1_4 ~ r*SAT1_3 + t*COM1_4

#regression: total effect of factors on Repurchase Intention 
C_REP1_4 ~ ac*Aesthetic + ad*Retail_Environment + ae*Assortment + af*French + ag*Gourmet + ah*High_end_Brands + ai*Fashionable + aj*Corporate_Image

#regression: total effect on Cocreation Intention 
C_CR1_4 ~ u*Aesthetic + v*Retail_Environment + w*Assortment + x*French + y*Gourmet + z*High_end_Brands + aa*Fashionable + ab*Corporate_Image'

# Define structural model for total effect
Model_Structural <- 
'# Indirect Effect factors to Repurchase Intention
aq := a*q
bq := b*q
cq := c*q
dq := d*q
eq := e*q
fq := f*q
gq := g*q
hq := h*q

# Indirect Effect factors to Cocreation Intention
ar := a*r
br := b*r
cr := c*r
dr := d*r
er := e*r
fr := f*r
gr := g*r
hr := h*r

# Indirect Effect factors to Repurchase Intention
is := i*s
js := j*s
ks := k*s
ls := l*s
ms := m*s
ns := n*s
os := o*s
ps := p*s

# Indirect Effect factors to Cocreation Intention
it := i*t
jt := j*t
kt := k*t
lt := l*t
mt := m*t
nt := n*t
ot := o*t
pt := p*t

#Total Indirect effect of factors to Repurchase Intention 
we := aq + is
te := bq + js
ye := cq + ks
ue := dq + ls
ie := eq + ms 
oe := fq + ns
pe := gq + os 
ae := hq + ps 

#Total Indirect effect of factors to Cocreation Intention 
se := ar + it 
de := br + jt
fe := cr + kt
ge := dr + lt
he := er + mt
je := fr + nt
ke := gr + ot
le := hr + pt 

# Total effect of factor on outcome Repurchase Intention 
te_fac1 := we + ac
te_fac2 := te + ad
te_fac3 := ye + ae
te_fac4 := ue + af
te_fac5 := ie + ag
te_fac6 := oe + ah 
te_fac7 := pe + ai
te_fac8 := ae + aj 

# Total effect of factor on outcome Cocreation Intention
te_fac12 := se + u
te_fac22 := de + v
te_fac32 := fe + w
te_fac42 := ge + x
te_fac52 := he + y
te_fac62 := je + z
te_fac72 := ke + aa
te_fac82 := le + ab
'

# Combine the model specification into a single string
model <- paste(Latent_Factors, Regression_Paths, Model_Structural, sep = "\n")

# Fit the model to the data
fit5 <- cfa(model = model, data = lafayette, missing = "ML")

# Inspect the output
summary(fit5, fit.measures = TRUE, standardized = TRUE)

6 Question

6.1 a) Are the mechanism driving satisfaction and affective commitment similar?

6.2 b) Are satisfaction and affective commitment mediating the impact of image perceptions on outcomes? If yes, for which outcomes?

We will start checking the model outputs before checking the path analysis results. The method we used for estimation is maximum likelihood (ML). The number of parameters in our model include both the number of estimated coefficients and number of variances and covariances is 158. Since we use the whole data set of Lafayette, the sample size is 553 observations. The model test user model has a test statistic 642.461 which indicates that the model fits the data reasonably well.The p-value suggests that the model fits the data well at 1.74 because it meets the threshold of below 5. The test statistic is very high (11429.390) with a large number of degrees of freedom (465), indicating a poor fit for the baseline model.The base-line model is rejected and user-model is better.The Comparative Fit Index (CFI) and Tucker-Lewis Index (TLI) are 0.975 and 0.969, respectively, indicating good model fit. The root mean square error of approximation (RMSEA) and standardized root mean square residual (SRMR) values are 0.037 and 0.043, indicating a good fit. Recall the optimal model under CFA, this model slightly is better in RMSEA since the 8-factor model without questions 8, 9, 11, and 15 was 4.0%. The log likelihood and information criteria are provided for model selection, with lower values indicating better model fit.

The latent variables results show that the model fits the data well and the latent variables are significantly related to their indicators.

a) Based on the output of regression of the mediators on the two outcomes, we can see that both SAT1_3 and COM1_4 have the same set of mechanisms: Aesthetic, Retail_Environment, Assortment, French, Gourmet, High_end_Brands, Fashionable, and Corporate_Image. However, the values associated with each mechanism are different for the two models.

Below are the factors (ranked) that drives the most satisfaction:

  • Corporate_Image

  • Assortment

  • Aesthetic

  • French

  • Retail_Environment

  • Gourmet

  • High_end_Brands

  • Fashionable

Below are the factors (ranked) that drives the most affective commitment:

  • Retail_Environment

b) We can look at the parameter estimates of the coefficients to answer this question. In particular, we look at the indirect effects of image perceptions on the outcomes through the mediators.

Based on the parameter estimates, factors of Retail Environment, Gourmet, Assortment and Corporate Image are significant for Repurchase Intention, therefore the mediation is significant for them as well. Specifically, Retail Environment has a positive indirect effect, while Gourmet, Assortment, and Corporate Image all have positive indirect effects with smaller effect sizes. The indirect effects of Aesthetic, French, High end brands, Fashionable for Repurchase Intention are not statistically significant.

On the other hand, the only indirect significant effect for Cocreation Intention is Retail Environment. Others are not statistically significant for this outcome meaning the mediation is not significant for them.

7 Question 3

What is driving the two distinct outcomes (repurchase and co-creation intention): Please rank the image dimensions with respect to the total effect on each outcome? Interpret your results.

Based on the parameter estimates we can extract below information about the total effect that factors have on the outcome.

For Repurchase Intention: - Retail Environment - Gourment - Corporate Image - French - Assortment - High End Brands - Aesthetic - Fashionable

For Cocreation Intention - Retail Intention - Corporate Image - Assortment - French - Fashionable - High End Brands - Aesthetic - Gourment
